    <abstract id="Abs1">
      <sec>
        <title>Background</title>
        <p id="Par1">An inverted repeat is a DNA sequence followed downstream by its reverse complement, potentially with a gap in the centre. Inverted repeats are found in both prokaryotic and eukaryotic genomes and they have been linked with countless possible functions. Many international consortia provide a comprehensive description of common genetic variation making alternative sequence representations, such as IUPAC encoding, necessary for leveraging the full potential of such broad variation datasets.</p>
      </sec>
      <sec>
        <title>Results</title>
        <p id="Par2">We present <sc>IUPACpal</sc>, an exact tool for efficient identification of inverted repeats in IUPAC-encoded DNA sequences allowing also for potential mismatches and gaps in the inverted repeats.</p>
      </sec>
      <sec>
        <title>Conclusion</title>
        <p id="Par3">Within the parameters that were tested, our experimental results show that <sc>IUPACpal</sc> compares favourably to a similar application packaged with <sc>EMBOSS</sc>. We show that <sc>IUPACpal</sc> identifies many previously unidentified inverted repeats when compared with <sc>EMBOSS</sc>, and that this is also performed with orders of magnitude improved speed.</p>
      </sec>
    </abstract>
