				\begin{document}$$\sigma \in \Sigma$$\end{document}</tex-math><mml:math id="M90"><mml:mrow><mml:mi>σ</mml:mi><mml:mo>∈</mml:mo><mml:mi mathvariant="normal">Σ</mml:mi></mml:mrow></mml:math><inline-graphic xlink:href="12859_2021_3983_Article_IEq45.gif"/></alternatives></inline-formula> may be treated as interchangeable for our purposes.</p>
      <p id="Par19">For degenerate strings, the notion of symbol equality is extended to symbol equality between degenerate symbols. Two degenerate symbols <inline-formula id="IEq46"><alternatives><tex-math id="M91">\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
				\usepackage{amsmath}
				\usepackage{wasysym} 
				\usepackage{amsfonts} 
				\usepackage{amssymb} 
				\usepackage{amsbsy}
				\usepackage{mathrsfs}
				\usepackage{upgreek}
				\setlength{\oddsidemargin}{-69pt}
				\begin{document}$${\tilde{x}}$$\end{document}</tex-math><mml:math id="M92"><mml:mover accent="true"><mml:mi>x</mml:mi><mml:mo stretchy="false">~</mml:mo></mml:mover></mml:math><inline-graphic xlink:href="12859_2021_3983_Article_IEq46.gif"/></alternatives></inline-formula> and <inline-formula id="IEq47"><alternatives><tex-math id="M93">\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
				\usepackage{amsmath}
